					ask_socfortress_message:
						'The SIGMA alert "Process Explorer Driver Creation By Non-Sysinternals Binary" indicates that a non-Sysinternals binary has created a driver using Process Explorer. This could be an indication of malicious activity or an unauthorized attempt to gain kernel-level access on a Windows endpoint.\n\nTo respond to this alert, you should conduct a thorough investigation to determine the nature and severity of the event. Here is an in-depth guide on key aspects to investigate:\n\n1. Analyze the process: Begin by examining the process that triggered the alert. Identify its name, path, and associated details such as command-line arguments, parent process, and user account executing it. Determine whether the process is legitimate or suspicious.\n\n2. Validate Sysinternals usage: Verify if Process Explorer (or any other Sysinternals tool) was legitimately used during this incident. Check if it was launched by authorized personnel for legitimate purposes like troubleshooting or system monitoring.\n\n3. Identify the driver creation: Investigate why a driver was created by the identified process. Determine if there is any legitimate reason for this action based on system configuration, software installation, or known activities.\n\n4. Ascertain binary legitimacy: Assess whether the non-Sysinternals binary used to create the driver is trusted and authorized within your environment. Check its digital signature status and reputation using antivirus/anti-malware tools or threat intelligence feeds.\n\n5. Analyze behavior: Evaluate any associated behaviors exhibited by this process or other related processes during this incident timeframe. Look for signs of further suspicious activity such as network connections, file modifications, registry changes, or privileged escalation attempts.\n\n6. Review system logs: Inspect relevant Windows event logs like Security Event Log (Event ID 4688 - Process Creation) and System Event Log (Event ID 7036 - Service Control Manager events) for additional information about process execution and service-related activities.\n\n7. Correlate with other events: Cross-reference this alert with other security events or indicators of compromise (IOCs) to identify any patterns or related incidents. Look for similar activities on other endpoints or network devices.\n\n8. Check for persistence mechanisms: Determine if the created driver is persistent across system reboots by investigating Windows service configurations, startup programs, scheduled tasks, and registry keys associated with system drivers.\n\n9. Assess impact: Evaluate the potential impact of this event on the affected endpoint and your overall environment. Consider whether sensitive data could be compromised, if lateral movement is possible, or if it indicates a broader attack campaign.\n\n10. Mitigation and response: Based on your investigation findings, determine an appropriate response strategy. This may involve isolating the affected endpoint from the network, disabling or removing suspicious drivers/services, conducting deeper forensic analysis, engaging incident response teams, or escalating to higher-level management for further action.\n\nAdditional questions to ask yourself when assessing this alert:\n\n1. Is there any known legitimate reason within your organization for a non-Sysinternals binary to create a driver using Process Explorer?\n2. Are there any authorized personnel who might have performed these actions? If so, verify their activity.\n3. Has this event been observed before? If yes, investigate previous instances to identify trends or recurring patterns.\n4. Are there any recent system changes or software installations that could explain this behavior?\n5. Have you received similar alerts from other security tools indicating potential malicious activity related to this process?\n6. Are there any open vulnerabilities on the affected endpoint that might have been exploited?\n7. Is there any correlation between this event and other ongoing incidents or threat intelligence reports?\n\nBy thoroughly investigating these aspects and asking additional pertinent questions specific to your environment, you can make informed decisions regarding containment, eradication of threats, and prevention of future incidents related to this SIGMA alert.',
