					ask_socfortress_message:
						'The SIGMA alert "Process Explorer Driver Creation By Non-Sysinternals Binary" suggests that a process explorer driver has been created by a binary that is not associated with Sysinternals. Process Explorer is a Windows system monitoring tool developed by Sysinternals (now part of Microsoft) that provides detailed information about running processes, including their DLLs and handles.\n\nWhen this alert triggers, it indicates that a non-Sysinternals binary has attempted to create or load a process explorer driver. This behavior can be suspicious because legitimate drivers for process exploration are typically signed and distributed by trusted sources like Sysinternals/Microsoft.\n\nTo respond to this alert effectively, you should consider the following key aspects:\n\n1. Source of the Binary: Determine the origin of the non-Sysinternals binary responsible for creating or loading the process explorer driver. Identify whether it comes from a reputable source or an unknown/untrusted entity.\n\n2. File Analysis: Conduct a thorough analysis of the binary file itself. Scan it using reputable antivirus software to check for any known malware signatures or indicators of compromise (IOCs). Analyze its metadata, such as digital signatures, timestamps, and file properties, to understand its legitimacy and purpose.\n\n3. Process Context: Investigate the context in which this activity occurred. Identify which user account was involved in loading the driver and review their level of privilege on the endpoint. Additionally, examine other related processes and activities happening at around the same time to identify any correlations or anomalous behaviors.\n\n4. Endpoint Visibility: Assess whether there are any indications of malicious activities on the affected endpoint(s). Look for signs of additional unauthorized tools or processes running alongside this activity using endpoint detection and response (EDR) solutions or system logs.\n\n5. Network Activity: Check if there have been any unusual network connections established from the affected endpoint during or after this event triggered. Look for communication with known malicious IP addresses, domains associated with command and control servers, or any data exfiltration attempts.\n\n6. TTP Mapping: Map the observed behavior to relevant Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs) enumerated by the MITRE ATT&CK framework. This step will help you understand the potential motivations and capabilities of the attacker behind this activity.\n\nWhen assessing this alert, ask yourself these additional questions:\n\n1. Is there a legitimate reason for a non-Sysinternals binary to create or load a process explorer driver? Validate whether any authorized software or applications on your network could be responsible for this behavior.\n\n2. Are there any known vulnerabilities or exploits associated with the process explorer driver that could potentially be targeted by attackers? Stay up-to-date with security advisories and vendor patches related to Process Explorer or similar tools.\n\n3. Are there any other security controls in place that might have blocked or logged this activity? Check if your endpoint protection platforms (EPP), intrusion detection systems (IDS), or security information and event management (SIEM) solutions have captured related events which might provide additional context.\n\n4. Have similar alerts been triggered before? Look for patterns of repeated alerts across different endpoints or timeframes to identify if this is an isolated incident or part of a broader attack campaign.\n\nRemember, each organization\'s response may vary based on their specific security policies, risk tolerance, and available resources.',
