					ask_socfortress_message:
						'The SIGMA alert you encountered, named "Process Explorer Driver Creation By Non-Sysinternals Binary," suggests that a non-Sysinternals binary has attempted to create a driver using Process Explorer. This alert could indicate potential malicious activity on the Windows endpoint.\n\nTo respond to this alert effectively, there are several key aspects you should investigate:\n\n1. Review Process Explorer: Begin by analyzing the Process Explorer tool itself. Understand its legitimate uses and the reasons why it is used within your organization. Determine if any authorized users or applications would have a valid reason to create a driver using Process Explorer.\n\n2. Identify the Binary: Investigate the non-Sysinternals binary that triggered the alert. Look for any suspicious characteristics such as unfamiliar file names, unexpected file locations, or digital signatures that do not match trusted vendors or publishers.\n\n3. Verify Legitimacy: If possible, compare the non-Sysinternals binary against known good samples or trusted sources to determine if it is a legitimate application or part of an unauthorized software installation.\n\n4. Assess Privileges and Permissions: Evaluate whether the process attempting to create a driver has sufficient privileges and permissions on the system to perform this action. Unauthorized attempts by low-privileged accounts may indicate an attempt at privilege escalation.\n\n5. Check for Persistence Mechanisms: Determine if this occurrence is part of a larger attack framework involving persistence mechanisms such as scheduled tasks, registry modifications, or other techniques that allow unauthorized binaries to execute automatically upon system startup.\n\n6. Analyze Network Connections: Look for any network connections originating from the system during or after the alert triggering event. Investigate these connections further to understand if they are related to known malicious activities or are communicating with suspicious IP addresses/domains.\n\n7. Monitor for Behavioral Anomalies: Analyze other indicators of compromise (IOCs) associated with this event such as unusual processes running in memory, unexpected modifications in critical files/registry keys, or abnormal system behavior. These can help identify the extent and impact of the potential intrusion.\n\nWhen assessing this alert, consider asking yourself the following additional questions:\n\n1. Is there any evidence indicating that this alert is a false positive? Consult with other security analysts or teams to validate the legitimacy of the alert.\n\n2. Are there any recent reports or indicators of similar attacks targeting your industry or organization? Researching recent trends and threat intelligence can provide context and aid in understanding the potential motivation behind this activity.\n\n3. What are the potential risks associated with allowing this activity to continue? Evaluate the impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability of sensitive data or critical systems.\n\n4. Are there any existing security controls or mitigations in place that could have prevented or detected this activity? Determine if any gaps exist in your current security infrastructure that need to be addressed.\n\n5. How should you communicate and collaborate with other teams within your organization to investigate and respond effectively? Identify who should be involved, such as incident response, network security, system administrators, legal/HR (if necessary), and engage them accordingly.\n\nRemember that each incident may vary in complexity, so adapt these steps as needed based on your organization\'s specific environment and incident response procedures.',
